Now I have the official details. Here's what happened:

## What broke

**DSA was removed from macOS in .NET 11 Preview 1** ([dotnet/docs#48201](https://github.com/dotnet/docs/issues/48201)).

.NET on macOS relied on Apple's **SecurityTransforms** library for DSA. Apple deprecated that library with no replacement. The Apple implementation was also limited — it only supported **DSA-1024 with SHA-1** (cryptographically weak) and never supported key generation. iOS/tvOS/MacCatalyst *never* had DSA support.

`DSA.Create()`, `DSACryptoServiceProvider`, and X.509 DSA certificate APIs now throw **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS. Linux (OpenSSL) and Windows (CNG) are unaffected.

## How to fix it

**Best option — migrate to ECDSA:**
```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create(ECCurve.NamedCurves.nistP256);
```
Re-sign legacy artifacts with ECDSA (or EdDSA). This is the recommended path.

**If you must still verify old DSA signatures cross-platform**, use a managed implementation like **BouncyCastle**:
```
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```
```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
verifier.Init(forSigning: false, dsaPublicKeyParameters);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

**If this is a temporary bridge**, you can also conditionally target:
```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    // BouncyCastle path
else
    // DSA.Create() path (still works on Linux/Windows)
```

**Bottom line**: Apple dropped DSA → .NET dropped it on macOS. Migrate to ECDSA for new signatures; use BouncyCastle for legacy DSA verification on macOS.
